      "question": "What is protocol-oriented programming, and how does it differ from classic OOP inheritance?",
      "answer": "POP models capabilities as **protocols** and shares behavior through **protocol extensions** rather than a base-class hierarchy. Instead of \"this `is-a` Animal,\" you say \"this `can` Fly\" — a type conforms to many small protocols, which composes far better than single inheritance and lets value types (structs, enums) participate in polymorphism, which class inheritance can't give them.\n\nThe enabling feature is the **protocol extension**: a default method implementation every conformer gets for free without a shared superclass.\n\nThe senior nuance is dispatch: a method that's a **protocol requirement** uses dynamic (witness-table) dispatch, so a conformer's implementation is honored through a protocol-typed variable. But a method that exists **only** in the extension (not in the requirement list) uses static dispatch — so a conformer's \"override\" of it won't be called through a protocol-typed reference. Knowing that line is what separates correct default-implementation design from subtle bugs.",
