      "question": "What is a retain cycle, and how do you break one?",
      "answer": "A **retain cycle** (strong reference cycle) happens when two or more objects hold strong references to each other, so neither's retain count ever reaches zero. ARC never frees them and the memory leaks, even though nothing outside the cycle can reach them.\n\nThe classic case is a parent holding a child strongly while the child holds the parent strongly; another is an object owning a closure that captures `self` strongly.\n\nYou break the cycle by making one edge non-owning:\n- Use `weak` for a back-reference that may legitimately become `nil` (a delegate, a child pointing back at its parent).\n- Use `unowned` when the back-reference is guaranteed never to outlive the object it points to, so it can never dangle.\n\nThe fix is always to demote exactly one direction of the cycle to a non-strong reference so the count can drain to zero.",
