      "id": "ios-life-3",
      "category": "lifecycle",
      "categoryLabel": "APP LIFECYCLE",
      "question": "In the SwiftUI `App` lifecycle, how do you observe state changes without a `UIApplicationDelegate`?",
      "answer": "SwiftUI exposes lifecycle through the environment value `@Environment(\\.scenePhase)`, a `ScenePhase` enum with cases `.active`, `.inactive`, and `.background` — there is no `suspended` case, since suspension runs no code.\n\nYou react with `.onChange(of: scenePhase)` on a `Scene` or `View`, for example flushing state to disk when it becomes `.background`.\n\nThe senior nuance: for process-level hooks SwiftUI doesn't surface (push-token registration, `didFinishLaunching`, third-party SDK init), you bridge back to UIKit with `@UIApplicationDelegateAdaptor`, which attaches a real `UIApplicationDelegate` to a pure-SwiftUI app.",
      "level": "mid"
