      "category": "lifecycle",
      "categoryLabel": "APP LIFECYCLE",
      "question": "An app needs ~20 seconds to finish an upload after the user backgrounds it. How do you keep it running, and what are the limits?",
      "answer": "For short finite work, wrap it in `beginBackgroundTask(withName:expirationHandler:)` and call `endBackgroundTask` when done. This buys extra wall-clock time before suspension, typically around 30 seconds (`backgroundTimeRemaining` reports what's left).\n\nThe expiration handler is mandatory: it must cancel the work and call `endBackgroundTask` synchronously. If you never end the task, the watchdog kills the app with `0x8badf00d`.\n\nThe senior nuance: a background task is the wrong tool for a real, possibly slow upload. The correct approach is `URLSession` with a **background configuration**, which hands the transfer to the system `nsurlsessiond` daemon so it completes — and relaunches your app to handle the result — even after your process is suspended or terminated.",
      "level": "senior"
